'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in Kamo, {{jalink|Kawanishi|Q609350}}, {{jalink|Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290}}. It is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}} of {{jalink|Kawabe District|Q1042053|Kōbe District}} in {{jalink|Settsu Province|Q864163}}, and its former rank was gōsha.

=== History ===
It enshrines the ancestral deity of the "Kamo Hōri-be" in {{jalink|Shinsen Shōjiroku}} under Settsu sacred lineages. Records were lost in a fire in the {{jalink|Tenmei|Q1194121}} era (1781-1788), but the shrine still possesses a single white-feather arrow said to have been dedicated by Prince Shino, an imperial descendant of {{jalink|Emperor Uda|Q349267}}.
* In August of {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}} 6 (1873), it became a village shrine.
* In February of Meiji 14 (1881), promoted to gōsha.
* In {{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 45 (1970), shrine buildings were newly built<ref>Sadatoshi Yoshii, "Shikinaisha Survey Report, Vol. 5" (1977) {{全国書誌番号|78005760}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{jalink|Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|Q11634943|Wakeikazuchi-no-Kami}}

=== Precinct shrines ===
As of 2019, the deities of precinct shrines are said to be completely unknown (hearing from the chief priest). Deity names from unclear sources are left here for reference.

* Kasuga Shrine {{jalink|Ame-no-Tajikarao|Q849412|Tajikarao-no-Mikoto}}
* Amaterasu Kōdaijin Shrine Hiwakamiya-no-Mikoto
* Atago Shrine Amekagutsuchi-no-Kami
* Taga Shrine {{jalink|Ōkuninushi|Q276944|Ōkuninushi-no-Kami}}
* Aragami Shrine Amekagutsuchi-no-Kami
* Kumano Shrine {{jalink|Izanagi|Q813858|Izanagi-no-Mikoto}}
* Inari Shrine Ōtsuki-hime-no-Mikoto
* Hachiman Shrine {{jalink|Emperor Ōjin|Q317997}}
* Matsuo Shrine Yasogami

