'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} in Kamo, {{ill|lt=Kawanishi|Q609350|WD=Q609350}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN}} of {{ill|lt=Kawabe District|Q1042053|WD=Q1042053|lt=Kōbe District}} in {{ill|lt=Settsu Province|Q864163|WD=Q864163}}, and its former rank was gōsha.

=== History ===
It enshrines the ancestral deity of the "Kamo Hōri-be" in {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|UNKNOWN}} under Settsu sacred lineages. Records were lost in a fire in the {{ill|lt=Tenmei|Q1194121|WD=Q1194121}} era (1781-1788), but the shrine still possesses a single white-feather arrow said to have been dedicated by Prince Shino, an imperial descendant of {{ill|lt=Emperor Uda|Q349267|WD=Q349267}}.
* In August of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096}} 6 (1873), it became a village shrine.
* In February of Meiji 14 (1881), promoted to gōsha.
* In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567}} 45 (1970), shrine buildings were newly built<ref>Sadatoshi Yoshii, "Shikinaisha Survey Report, Vol. 5" (1977) {{全国書誌番号|78005760}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{ill|lt=Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|Q11634943|WD=Q11634943|lt=Wakeikazuchi-no-Kami}}

=== Precinct shrines ===
As of 2019, the deities of precinct shrines are said to be completely unknown (hearing from the chief priest). Deity names from unclear sources are left here for reference.

* Kasuga Shrine {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Tajikarao|Q849412|WD=Q849412|lt=Tajikarao-no-Mikoto}}
* Amaterasu Kōdaijin Shrine Hiwakamiya-no-Mikoto
* Atago Shrine Amekagutsuchi-no-Kami
* Taga Shrine {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi-no-Kami}}
* Aragami Shrine Amekagutsuchi-no-Kami
* Kumano Shrine {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|WD=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto}}
* Inari Shrine Ōtsuki-hime-no-Mikoto
* Hachiman Shrine {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997}}
* Matsuo Shrine Yasogami

