'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kamo, {{ill|lt=Kawanishi|Q609350|WD=Q609350|1=Kawanishi, Hyōgo}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} of {{ill|lt=Kawabe District|Q1042053|WD=Q1042053|lt=Kōbe District|1=Kawabe District, Hyōgo}} in {{ill|lt=Settsu Province|Q864163|WD=Q864163|1=Settsu Province}}, and its former rank was gōsha.

=== History ===
It enshrines the ancestral deity of the "Kamo Hōri-be" in {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|1=UNKNOWN}} under Settsu sacred lineages. Records were lost in a fire in the {{ill|lt=Tenmei|Q1194121|WD=Q1194121|1=Tenmei}} era (1781-1788), but the shrine still possesses a single white-feather arrow said to have been dedicated by Prince Shino, an imperial descendant of {{ill|lt=Emperor Uda|Q349267|WD=Q349267|1=Emperor Uda}}.
* In August of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 (1873), it became a village shrine.
* In February of Meiji 14 (1881), promoted to gōsha.
* In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 45 (1970), shrine buildings were newly built<ref>Sadatoshi Yoshii, "Shikinaisha Survey Report, Vol. 5" (1977) {{全国書誌番号|78005760}}</ref>.

